Because of performance limitations of Taverna (in particular concerning pipelining among the services), we developped MOTEUR, a Scufl enactor dedicated to the execution of Taverna workflows on EGEE. column25: One of our major research activities is the analysis of the structure and function of bacterial ion channels and efflux systems. E. coli cells possess at least four classes of ion channels - mechanosensitive (MscL, MscS, MscM, KefA), ligand-gated (KefB, KefC), Shaker-like (Kch) and chloride (CLC). Our work on MscS, MscK and KefC has advanced to the stage where the physiological role of the channels is understood, the principal basis of gating is clear and molecular analysis of the gating is quite advanced. Our major goals are to marry the genetic and physiological insights with structural information through protein biochemistry and crystallography.

column25: My name is Kelsey Moody, and I am an undergraduate attending the State University of New York (SUNY), Plattsburgh.  I have completed a major in psychology and am currently working to finish a second in biochemistry, with the intent of pursuing an MD/PhD.  My research interests localize around regenerative medicine and human aging.  I am currently investigating how oxidation of cathepsin D inhibits its ability to degrade tau protein.  This research is relevant to Alzheimer's disease (AD) as accumulation of hyperphosphorylated tau is prevalent in AD patients and literature review validates our hypothesis, demonstrating that oxidation of other forms of cathepsin inhibit function.  In addition to this research project, I also oversee a psychology team which is investigating public skepticism of innovative science.  I also serve as Academic Coordinator for SENS Foundation, and am responsible for running SENS Foundation's Academic Initiative (SENSFAI), a student-focused research and development program which promotes research, training, and interest in regenerative medicine.

column25: I am a General Surgery Resident at the University of Chicago (USA) completing a research year focusing on computational modeling of gut-derived sepsis and virulence acitvation in Pseudomonas aeruginosa. In collaboration with Dr Gary An at Northwestern University (Chicago, IL USA), we are developing agent-based models (ABM) to simulate complex cross-talk signaling between colonizing opportunistic pathogens and the stressed host. The laboratory of Dr John Alverdy (University of Chicago) has resolved several mechanisms of virulence activation in Pseudomonas aeruginosa in response to shifts in the intestinal mucosal microenvironment and interception of host signaling during stress. We are currently developing ABM's to instantiate multiple components of the gut milieu to capture emergent patterns in pathogen and host behavior. In addition, I have integrated a beta phase Wiki application at our University (Confluence) into the lab meetings as a local resource repository and am seeking new applications with interfaces such as myExperiment. My background is in clinical science (Surgery) and laboratory research.
I am currently employed by Astrazeneca. As a consequence, the workflows developed previously to this employment (before 5th September 2011) may no longer be supported.

column25: I am the Head of the Data Library at the University of Alberta and the Academic Director of the Research Data Centre.  I have spent the past 25 years of my career providing research data services at my University.  I began as a statistical consultant in an academic computing centre and while data analysis remains an interest, I found myself championing the stewardship of data when few people had the same interest.  I was very fortunate to turn my affinity for data into a career at a leading Canadian research university.  In the past fifteen years, I have been actively involved with the Data Liberation Initiative (DLI) in Canada to provide affordable and equitable access to Statistics Canada data.  This has led at movement of establishing data services in libraries in post-secondary institutions.  There are now 75 members institutions in DLI.  I have also been active in establishing a training programme that holds four regional workshops across Canada annually to provide continuing education and skills development around data services.

column25: The future plans are to use Taverna for creating workflows in the metabolomics field: create, connect and build webservices for the Netherlands Metabolomic Center, a Dutch national platform for metabolomics.

Now, senior scientist, I have been sticking to the bench from 1989 until 2007 as a bio-[techno]-logist. I moved to Belgium as a young PostDoc ('93) in a lab which later became part of VIB. I stayed at VIB (in 2 different Departments / 4 different groups) since then. I finally left the bench (the glue was not strong anymore :-) ) and joined BITS as data-miner in Sept 2007 to promote biocomputing among my fellow scientists.

column25: Marine ecosystems provide a wide range of economically important products and services to the community and these functions are directly dependent on the biological diversity in these environments. Today, we note major changes in the biodiversity composition of our marine ecosystems, but we have poor control over how large and extensive they are because there is no organized and standardized monitoring system over a wider geographical perspective. At the same time there is no analytical approach available that combines diverse biological disciplines, i.e. ecological, taxonomic, climatic, and genetic data. The practical impossibility to assemble and analyze such complex data sets across large geographic distances is perhaps the most crucial obstacle for biodiversity research to become a dominant scientific discipline in the future. A part of my research will focuses on facilitating meta-analysis of such diverse information in order to understand the changes and functions in marine ecosystems.

My main research is in providing assistance and solutions to challenges with research activity through the use of text mining techniques. As part of this goal my research is focussed upon large scale information retrieval tasks and how they can be improved through the integration of text and data mining tools with natural language processing algorithms. In order to achieve the scalability of solutions this has been investigated alongside distributed computing techniques. To complement the technical development and application provision I am interested in the human factors associated with non-expert use of these tools, in particular the seemingly self imposed barriers built by arts and humanities users. Therefore usability studies and interface development are key issues during the development and evaluation phases of my research.
